div.p:
I haue one thing more to name yet, that tels vs what great cause we haue to feare; greater this then any of the other. Will you aske what it is? It is the invndation of Sinne, that so immeasurably ouerflowes in all

places of this land. Oh the crying sinnes, the crying sinnes of this land; they will neuer let heauen be at rest, till it haue sent them a scourge. It is an admirable peice of newes that our late Gallo-Belgicus reports about the towne of Pleurs,
                  Page 4. I told you of euen now; that was so strangely subuerted vpon the sudden, and lies buried to this day vnder it's owne ashes, without hope of any possible restauration. A while after the subuersion of it, diuers neighbourers that repaired thither would needes attempt to dig into the ground that they might see what they could finde. Among other things that they found, God directed them to a Stone, which when they had taken vp, they saw something written vpon it in Hebrew letters, as if (like the Tables of Stone, that were giuen to Moses in mount Sinai) it had beene grauen with Gods own finger. The writing was this;
